The matching procedure described—where students apply to their top remaining choice, schools identify their highest priority student among all remaining students, and matches occur via closed loops (cycles) of applications and identifications—is equivalent to the Top Trading Cycles (TTC) mechanism for single-unit quotas. A key property of the TTC mechanism is that it is strategy-proof for the student side (the proposing side). This means that a student cannot achieve a better outcome (according to their true preferences) by submitting a dishonest preference list than by submitting their true preference list. 

Therefore, the optimal strategy for Student B is to report their True Preference List truthfully.

3. Cycle: S_B applies to H_A. H_A identifies S_E. S_E applies to H_C. H_C identifies S_B. (S_B -> H_A -> S_E -> H_C -> S_B).
4. Matches: (S_B, H_A) [Rank 1 for B], (S_E, H_C) [Rank 1 for E].

This sequential process is analogous to a Top Trading Cycles (TTC) variation, where the proposing side (Students) often benefits from truthful reporting.

This is characteristic of the Student-Optimal Top Trading Cycles (TTC) algorithm. A key property of the TTC mechanism is that submitting true preferences is generally a weakly dominant strategy for the agents initiating the applications (the students). Therefore, submitting the true preference list is the optimal strategy to maximize the rank of the assigned school.
